@node Buffer protection
@section Buffer protection

@vindex claude-code-extras-protect-buffers
@vindex claude-code-extras-warn-kill-with-branches
The user option @code{claude-code-extras-protect-buffers} controls whether killing a Claude Code buffer requires confirmation. When set to non-@code{nil} (the default), any attempt to kill a buffer with a live Claude process triggers a @samp{yes-or-no-p} prompt. This prevents accidental loss of an active session. When the process has already exited (e.g. via the @samp{/exit} command inside Claude), the prompt is skipped.

The user option @code{claude-code-extras-warn-kill-with-branches} controls whether exiting a Claude Code session via @samp{/exit} prompts for confirmation when the session has branches (created via @samp{/branch}). This is a separate guard from @code{claude-code-extras-protect-buffers}: the buffer-kill guard prevents accidental closure, while the branch guard reminds you that related sessions exist. The check scans session JSONL headers in the project directory (fast, first-line only) to count branches. If the session has at least one branch, the prompt reports the count (e.g. ``Session has 3 branches --- kill anyway?''). If declined, the buffer is kept alive even though the process has exited, giving you a chance to use @code{claude-code-extras-switch-branch} (@ref{Branch navigation}) first.

Both options default to @code{t}. Set either to @code{nil} to disable the corresponding prompt.

@node Diff display
@section Diff display

@findex claude-code-extras--display-diff-buffer
The function @code{claude-code-extras--display-diff-buffer} overrides @code{monet--display-diff-buffer} to display diff buffers in a bottom side window instead of using @code{display-buffer-in-tab}. The upstream implementation calls @code{display-buffer-in-tab} from an async websocket callback, which switches tabs as a side effect and can corrupt the window layout when the fallback @code{display-buffer-pop-up-window} fails and Emacs resorts to @code{display-buffer-use-some-window} (which replaces the buffer in an existing window). The override avoids tab switching entirely.

@node Terminal rendering
@section Terminal rendering

@vindex claude-code-extras-sigwinch-delay
The user option @code{claude-code-extras-sigwinch-delay} specifies the delay (in seconds) before sending a @samp{SIGWINCH} signal to the Claude process after startup. This works around a race condition where the TUI queries terminal dimensions before the Eat terminal window is fully laid out, resulting in a garbled banner. The default value is @samp{0.5}. Increase it if you still see rendering artifacts on slower machines.

@findex claude-code-extras-disable-scrollback-truncation
The function @code{claude-code-extras-disable-scrollback-truncation} sets @code{eat-term-scrollback-size} to @samp{nil} in Claude Code buffers. Eat's default scrollback limit of 8192 lines causes early output to be silently discarded in long sessions. This function is added to @code{claude-code-start-hook} automatically.

@node Theme sync
@section Theme sync

@vindex claude-code-extras-sync-theme
The user option @code{claude-code-extras-sync-theme} controls whether Claude Code sessions are kept in sync with the current Emacs theme. When non-@code{nil}, changing the Emacs theme (via @code{enable-theme-functions}) re-runs @code{/theme} in all running Claude Code sessions, forcing Claude Code to re-query the terminal background via the OSC 11 escape sequence. The default value is @code{nil} (disabled).

This assumes Claude Code is configured with the @code{auto} theme globally (in @samp{~/.claude.json}). The @code{auto} theme detects the terminal background at startup but does not continuously re-probe, so re-running @code{/theme} is what triggers re-detection mid-session.

Sessions that are idle (waiting for user input) receive the @code{/theme} command immediately. Sessions where Claude is still generating a response queue the re-selection and apply it automatically when the turn finishes (via the Stop hook). Because @code{/theme} is a client-side slash command that does not start a new turn, the session's idle state is preserved across re-selections, so subsequent Emacs theme toggles continue to apply immediately rather than queueing indefinitely.

The theme sync is fully asynchronous: the @code{enable-theme-functions} hook returns immediately, and all terminal interactions are deferred to zero-delay timers.  This prevents reentrant timer execution (e.g. @code{org-roam-db-sync}) from blocking the main thread during @code{accept-process-output}.

The busy/idle dispatch and the Stop-hook re-selection are covered by ERT tests in @samp{emacs/extras/test/claude-code-extras-test.el} under the @samp{Theme sync busy/idle handling} section.

@node Alert options
@section Alert options

@vindex claude-code-extras-alert-on-ready
@vindex claude-code-extras-alert-style
@vindex claude-code-extras-alert-sound
The user option @code{claude-code-extras-alert-on-ready} controls whether the user is notified when Claude needs attention. The default is @code{nil} (no alerts). Toggle it interactively with @code{claude-code-extras-toggle-alert} (@ref{Toggling alerts}).

The user option @code{claude-code-extras-alert-style} determines the type of notification. It accepts one of three values: @code{visual} (an OS notification via the @samp{alert} package), @code{sound} (an audio alert), or @code{both} (the default when alerts are enabled). This option only takes effect when @code{claude-code-extras-alert-on-ready} is non-@code{nil}.

The user option @code{claude-code-extras-alert-sound} specifies the path to the sound file played for audible alerts. The default is @samp{/System/Library/Sounds/Glass.aiff}, a macOS system sound. Change this to any audio file that @samp{afplay} can handle.

@node Account options
@section Account options

@vindex claude-code-extras-accounts
The user option @code{claude-code-extras-accounts} is an alist of @samp{(NAME . CONFIG-DIR)} pairs for switching between multiple Claude OAuth accounts without re-authenticating. See @ref{Multi-account support} for details and configuration examples. The default is @code{nil} (single-account mode).

@vindex claude-code-extras-account-file
The user option @code{claude-code-extras-account-file} is the file where the active account name is persisted across Emacs sessions. The default is @samp{~/.claude-current-account}.

@node Copilot options
@section Copilot options

@vindex claude-code-extras-copilot-enabled
The user option @code{claude-code-extras-copilot-enabled} controls whether Copilot ghost-text completions are enabled in Claude Code buffers. The default is @code{nil} (disabled). When set to non-@code{nil}, @code{copilot-mode} is automatically activated in new Claude Code buffers, and an adapter routes accepted completions through the Eat terminal emulator instead of inserting them directly into the buffer. Completions are suppressed while Claude is responding (i.e. when the buffer is read-only). The @samp{copilot} package must be installed for this feature to work; if it is not available, the setup is silently skipped.

@node Batch TODO processing options
@section Batch TODO processing options

@vindex claude-code-extras-log-directory
The user option @code{claude-code-extras-log-directory} specifies the directory where batch processing output is saved. The default value is the @samp{claude-logs} subdirectory under @code{paths-dir-notes}.

@vindex claude-code-extras-batch-permission-mode
@vindex claude-code-extras-batch-allowed-tools
@vindex claude-code-extras-batch-max-turns
@vindex claude-code-extras-batch-system-prompt
@vindex claude-code-extras-batch-model
The user option @code{claude-code-extras-batch-permission-mode} specifies the permission mode passed via @samp{--permission-mode} for non-interactive execution. The default is @samp{"auto"}, which uses a background classifier to allow most actions while blocking risky ones.

The user option @code{claude-code-extras-batch-allowed-tools} specifies which tools are auto-allowed via @samp{--allowedTools} for non-interactive execution (batch TODO processing, skill runner, and project audit). The default includes @samp{Bash}, @samp{Read}, @samp{Write}, @samp{Edit}, @samp{Glob}, @samp{Grep}, @samp{WebFetch}, and @samp{WebSearch}. Adjust this list to restrict or expand what Claude can do autonomously.

The user option @code{claude-code-extras-batch-max-turns} controls the maximum number of agentic turns per entry in non-interactive execution. The default is 30. Increase it for complex tasks that require many tool calls; decrease it to bound execution time.

The user option @code{claude-code-extras-batch-system-prompt} specifies an optional system prompt appended via @samp{--append-system-prompt} to each @samp{claude -p} invocation. The default is @code{nil} (no extra system prompt).

The user option @code{claude-code-extras-batch-model} specifies an optional model override via @samp{--model}. The default is @code{nil} (use Claude's default model).

@vindex claude-code-extras-org-todo-in-progress-keyword
The user option @code{claude-code-extras-org-todo-in-progress-keyword} specifies an Org TODO keyword to set on a heading when it is sent to Claude Code via @code{claude-code-extras-send-todo-at-point} (@ref{Send TODO at point}).  The keyword must be one of the values configured in @code{org-todo-keywords} for the current buffer.  The default value is @code{nil}, meaning the TODO state is not changed.  Since Org's built-in keywords are just @code{TODO} and @code{DONE}, with no intermediate ``in progress'' state, this option is disabled by default.  Users who have configured a workflow with an in-progress keyword (e.g. @code{DOING}, @code{IN-PROGRESS}, @code{STARTED}) can set this option to that keyword.

@node Project audit options
@section Project audit options

@vindex claude-code-extras-audit-skills
The user option @code{claude-code-extras-audit-skills} specifies the list of skills to run when performing a project audit via @code{claude-code-extras-audit-project}. Each entry is a skill name with a leading slash. The default value is @code{("/code-audit" "/design-audit" "/interpretability-audit")}. Each skill is invoked with @samp{--accept}, which instructs it to auto-fix all findings without prompting. Customize this list to add, remove, or reorder audit passes.

@vindex claude-code-extras-audit-project-directories
The user option @code{claude-code-extras-audit-project-directories} specifies the directories available for selection when running @code{claude-code-extras-audit-project}. When the user enters a directory not already in this list, it is automatically appended and persisted via @code{customize-save-variable}, so it will appear as a candidate in future invocations.

@node Debug backtrace options
@section Debug backtrace options

@vindex claude-code-extras-debug-backtrace-model
The user option @code{claude-code-extras-debug-backtrace-model} sets the gptel model used to identify candidate packages from a backtrace. The default is @code{gemini-flash-lite-latest}, a fast and cheap model suited for this simple classification task.

@vindex claude-code-extras-debug-backtrace-backend
The user option @code{claude-code-extras-debug-backtrace-backend} sets the gptel backend name for backtrace analysis. The default is @code{"Gemini"}.

The backtrace analysis request explicitly disables @code{gptel-use-tools} so that tool definitions are never sent to the model, keeping the request lightweight and avoiding unexpected tool-call responses.

@node Status polling options
@section Status polling options

@vindex claude-code-extras-status-interval
The user option @code{claude-code-extras-status-interval} sets the polling frequency (in seconds) for reading the status JSON file. The default is 5. Lower values give more responsive modeline updates; higher values reduce filesystem polling overhead.

@node Usage polling options
@section Usage polling options

@vindex claude-code-extras-usage-interval
@vindex claude-code-extras-usage-max-interval
The user option @code{claude-code-extras-usage-interval} sets the base polling frequency (in seconds) for querying the Anthropic usage API@. The default is 300 (5 minutes). This controls how often @code{claude-code-extras-start-usage-polling} (@ref{Usage polling}) fetches updated utilization data from the @samp{api/oauth/usage} endpoint.

When the API responds with HTTP 429 (rate limited), the polling interval doubles automatically until it reaches @code{claude-code-extras-usage-max-interval} (default 900 seconds, i.e. 15 minutes). On the next successful response, the interval resets to the base value. This exponential backoff avoids hammering an undocumented endpoint that enforces strict rate limits.

