@node Session switching
@section Session switching

@findex claude-code-extras-start-or-switch
The command @code{claude-code-extras-start-or-switch} is the main entry point for working with Claude sessions. When no Claude sessions are active, it starts a new one by calling @code{claude-code}. When one or more sessions exist, it opens a two-column transient menu.  The left column lists active sessions, each bound to a home-row key (@samp{a}, @samp{s}, @samp{d}, @samp{f}, @samp{j}, @samp{k}, @samp{l}, @samp{;}) for single-keystroke switching.  The right column contains actions: @samp{w} to jump to the most recently waiting session and @samp{n} to start a new session.

Each session is assigned a key when it starts (via @code{claude-code-start-hook}). The assignment persists for the lifetime of the session: killing a buffer releases its key, and the freed key is reused by the next session that starts. Dead-buffer entries are automatically purged before each assignment, so keys are always recycled promptly. When the transient opens, any sessions that predate the key system (e.g. sessions started before the package was loaded) are retroactively assigned keys.

Sessions are displayed by project name (extracted from the buffer name). When multiple sessions share the same project, the instance name is appended for disambiguation (e.g. ``project:instance'').

@vindex claude-code-extras-waiting
Sessions that are waiting for user input (detected via the @samp{idle_prompt} notification hook) are displayed with the @code{claude-code-extras-waiting} face, which inherits from @code{warning} by default.  The highlight is cleared as soon as input is sent to the session (Return key or programmatic command send).

@findex claude-code-extras-jump-to-waiting
The command @code{claude-code-extras-jump-to-waiting} (bound to @samp{w} in the session switcher) switches to the session that most recently started waiting for user input.  This is useful when an alert sound fires but the notification is missed: pressing @samp{w} jumps straight to the session that triggered it without needing to scan the list.  If no sessions are currently waiting, it displays a message.

