@node Multi-account support
@subsection Multi-account support

@vindex claude-code-extras-accounts
When @code{claude-code-extras-accounts} is non-nil, each account maps to a separate @samp{CLAUDE_CONFIG_DIR}, so OAuth credentials, settings, and memory are kept independent. This avoids the need to log out and back in when switching between accounts (e.g. tlon and epoch).

Configure accounts as an alist of @samp{(NAME . CONFIG-DIR)} pairs:

@lisp
(setopt claude-code-extras-accounts
        '(("personal" . "~/.claude-personal")
          ("tlon"     . "~/.claude-tlon")
          ("epoch"    . "~/.claude-epoch")))
@end lisp

@findex claude-code-extras-select-account
The active account is persisted across sessions (in @code{claude-code-extras-account-file}). Use @code{claude-code-extras-select-account} to change it. In the transient menu (@ref{Transient menu}), the Options column includes an ``account'' infix (bound to @code{-a}) that displays the currently active account name and lets you switch accounts by pressing the key.  @code{claude-code-extras-start-or-switch} uses the persisted account silently; if no account has been selected yet, it prompts once and saves the choice. If only one account is configured, it is selected automatically.

@findex claude-code-extras-init-account
Before a new account's first @samp{claude} run, call @code{claude-code-extras-init-account} to create its config directory and set up the shared symlinks.  This avoids a bootstrap race where @samp{claude} writes fresh empty files into the account directory before the sync can symlink them, leaving permissions and history isolated from the rest of your setup.  @code{claude-code-extras-select-account} also runs the same setup implicitly, so either entry point works.  The function is safe to re-run: it heals virgin-state files (empty @samp{settings.json}, empty directories) by replacing them with symlinks, and leaves real content alone with a warning.

The first time you start a session with a given account, Claude will prompt for OAuth login. After that, switching is instant.

@findex claude-code-extras--account-env
Every code path that launches a session -- including @code{claude-code-extras--start-with-account}, @code{claude-code-extras-restart}, @code{claude-code-extras-handoff}, the branch navigation commands, and @code{claude-code-extras--debug-start-session} -- routes @samp{CLAUDE_CONFIG_DIR} through @code{claude-code-extras--account-env}.  That function prefers the dynamically bound @code{claude-code-extras--pending-account} (set by the smart-start entry points) and falls back to @code{claude-code-extras--resolve-account} (the persisted active account) when the binding is absent.  The fallback ensures direct calls to @code{claude-code--start} still pick the right account instead of silently using @samp{~/.claude/}.

@findex claude-code-extras--ensure-shared-symlinks
@vindex claude-code-extras--shared-config-items
@vindex claude-code-extras--shared-claude-json-keys
When a session starts, @code{claude-code-extras--sync-account-config} performs two kinds of synchronization:

@enumerate
@item
@strong{Symlinked items} (listed in @code{claude-code-extras--shared-config-items}): @samp{settings.json}, @samp{settings.local.json}, @samp{skills}, @samp{plugins}, @samp{projects}, @samp{memory}, and @samp{history.jsonl} are symlinked from @samp{~/.claude/} into the account's config directory.  This shares permissions, hooks, skills, plugins, project trust, memory, and session history across accounts.

@item
@strong{Merged @samp{.claude.json} keys}: @samp{theme}, @samp{claudeInChromeDefaultEnabled}, and @samp{hasCompletedClaudeInChromeOnboarding} (listed in @code{claude-code-extras--shared-claude-json-keys}) are copied verbatim from the canonical @samp{~/.claude.json} into each account's @samp{.claude.json}.  The @samp{mcpServers} key is deep-merged per-server: server definitions are copied from canonical, but per-account @samp{env} entries are preserved so that account-specific credentials (e.g. @samp{op://} references for API keys) survive the sync.  The @samp{projects} key is merged separately using trust-aware logic.  This ensures MCP servers and UI preferences are available in every account without sharing account-specific data like OAuth credentials.
@end enumerate

Existing files or directories that are not symlinks are inspected: if they are in a @strong{virgin state} (empty, or a JSON file containing only @samp{\@{\@}} or @samp{[]}, or an empty directory), they are deleted and replaced with a symlink to the canonical location.  Targets with real content are left untouched and a warning is logged, so the user can migrate data manually and then re-run @code{claude-code-extras-init-account}.  The @samp{.claude.json} write is skipped when no changes are detected, to avoid triggering file-change watchers.

@node Toggling alerts
@section Toggling alerts

@findex claude-code-extras-toggle-alert
The command @code{claude-code-extras-toggle-alert} toggles the buffer-local value of @code{claude-code-extras-alert-on-ready} and reports the new state. This is useful during long-running operations: enable alerts before submitting a complex prompt, then disable them when you return to interactive use. The alert style and sound are configured via the user options described in @ref{Alert options}.

@node Usage polling
@section Usage polling

@findex claude-code-extras-start-usage-polling
@findex claude-code-extras-stop-usage-polling
The command @code{claude-code-extras-start-usage-polling} begins periodic polling of the Anthropic @samp{api/oauth/usage} endpoint to track plan utilization. The data is fetched asynchronously via @code{url-retrieve} for each account with an active session. Authentication uses the per-account OAuth token from the macOS Keychain, where each @code{CLAUDE_CONFIG_DIR} has its own credential entry (service name @samp{Claude Code-credentials-<sha256prefix>}). The fetched data is stored in a hash table keyed by account name, so each session's modeline shows its own account's rate limit status. Calling this command when polling is already active is a no-op.

Polling starts automatically when a Claude Code modeline is set up (via @code{claude-code-extras-set-modeline}, @ref{Modeline integration}), so manual invocation is rarely needed. The polling interval is controlled by @code{claude-code-extras-usage-interval} (@ref{Usage polling options}), with automatic exponential backoff on HTTP 429 responses.

The command @code{claude-code-extras-stop-usage-polling} cancels the usage polling timer. Use it to stop background API requests when they are no longer needed.

The polled data is exposed through four accessor functions described in @ref{Usage accessors}.

@node Skill runner
@section Skill runner

@findex claude-code-extras-run-skill
The command @code{claude-code-extras-run-skill} runs a Claude Code skill non-interactively via @samp{claude -p}. Interactively, it prompts for the skill name with completion (annotated with descriptions), then for arguments if the skill declares an @samp{argument-hint} in its frontmatter, and finally for a working directory. The result is displayed in a @samp{*Claude Skill: <name>*} buffer in org-mode with cost, duration, and session ID@.

Only skills with @samp{user-invocable: true} (or no @samp{user-invocable} field) in their @samp{SKILL.md} frontmatter are offered for completion. Skills are discovered from @samp{~/.claude/skills/} (global) and the current project's @samp{.claude/skills/} directory. Project skills shadow global skills with the same name. The completion UI annotates each candidate with a @samp{[global]} or @samp{[project]} tag to indicate its source.

The command uses the same non-interactive execution infrastructure as batch TODO processing, respecting @code{claude-code-extras-batch-allowed-tools}, @code{claude-code-extras-batch-max-turns}, @code{claude-code-extras-batch-system-prompt}, and @code{claude-code-extras-batch-model} (@ref{Batch TODO processing options}).

@node Batch TODO processing
@section Batch TODO processing

@findex claude-code-extras-batch-todos
The command @code{claude-code-extras-batch-todos} processes org TODO entries sequentially via @samp{claude -p} in non-interactive mode. It must be called from an org-mode buffer. Scope is inferred automatically: @samp{region} if the region is active, @samp{subtree} if the buffer is narrowed, @samp{buffer} otherwise. The command then prompts for a working directory via @code{project-prompt-project-dir}. A confirmation prompt is shown unless the scope is @samp{region} (where the explicit selection already signals intent).

Each TODO's heading becomes the prompt (with body text appended if present). Entries are processed sequentially — each @samp{claude -p} invocation must finish before the next starts. Errors do not abort the batch; each failure is recorded and processing continues.

Results are saved as JSON log files in a timestamped subdirectory under @code{claude-code-extras-log-directory} (@ref{Batch TODO processing options}). When all entries have been processed, a @samp{*Claude Batch Results*} summary buffer is displayed in org-mode with per-entry status, cost, duration, log file links, and Claude's response text.

The command respects @code{claude-code-extras-batch-allowed-tools}, @code{claude-code-extras-batch-max-turns}, @code{claude-code-extras-batch-system-prompt}, and @code{claude-code-extras-batch-model} (@ref{Batch TODO processing options}).

@node Send TODO at point
@section Send TODO at point

@findex claude-code-extras-send-todo-at-point
The command @code{claude-code-extras-send-todo-at-point} sends the org TODO heading at point to a running interactive Claude Code session. Unlike @code{claude-code-extras-batch-todos} (@ref{Batch TODO processing}), which processes entries non-interactively via @samp{claude -p}, this command targets a live TUI session where the user can review Claude's output and intervene between tasks.

The intended workflow is a split window with the org buffer on one side and the Claude Code session on the other. After reviewing Claude's output for one task, the user moves point to the next TODO heading and invokes the command again.

Session resolution is automatic via @code{claude-code-extras--resolve-session-for-file}: if the org file belongs to a project and exactly one Claude Code session is running in that project, it is used directly with no prompt. When multiple sessions exist for the project, the user is prompted to select one. When no project is detected or no session matches, it falls back to the standard @code{claude-code--get-or-prompt-for-buffer} selection.

The prompt sent to the session is the cleaned heading text—stripped of the TODO keyword, priority, and tags—followed by the entry body (if any) separated by a blank line.  Org inline markup is converted to Markdown equivalents before sending: verbatim (@code{=…=}) and code (@samp{~…~}) markers become backticks, so the prompt reads naturally in the Claude Code session.

When @code{claude-code-extras-org-todo-in-progress-keyword} is non-@code{nil}, the heading's TODO state is changed to that keyword after the prompt is sent (@ref{Batch TODO processing options}).  This provides a visual indication in the org buffer of which tasks have been dispatched to Claude.

@node Project audit
@section Project audit

@findex claude-code-extras-audit-project
The command @code{claude-code-extras-audit-project} runs a comprehensive audit of a project. It prompts the user to select a directory from @code{claude-code-extras-audit-project-directories} (@ref{Project audit options}) or enter a new one. New directories are automatically added to the list for future use. It then sequentially invokes each skill in @code{claude-code-extras-audit-skills} (@ref{Project audit options}) with @samp{--accept}, each as a separate non-interactive @samp{claude -p} session. This means each audit starts with a fresh context window.

After each audit completes successfully, any uncommitted changes in the project directory are automatically committed with a message of the form @samp{<skill>: apply audit recommendations}. This ensures each audit's changes are isolated in their own commit, making them easy to review individually.

The command reuses the batch processing infrastructure (@ref{Batch TODO internals}), so results are logged and displayed in the same @samp{*Claude Batch Results*} summary buffer with per-audit status, cost, duration, and output. The batch options (@code{claude-code-extras-batch-max-turns}, @code{claude-code-extras-batch-model}, etc.) apply to audit runs as well.

@node Debug backtrace
@section Debug backtrace

@findex claude-code-extras-debug-backtrace
The command @code{claude-code-extras-debug-backtrace} automates the workflow of debugging an Emacs backtrace with Claude Code. When invoked from a @samp{*Backtrace*} buffer, it:

@enumerate
@item
Saves the backtrace to the downloads directory via @code{debug-save-backtrace}.
@item
Sends the backtrace to a light LLM (configured via @code{claude-code-extras-debug-backtrace-model} and @code{claude-code-extras-debug-backtrace-backend}, @ref{Debug backtrace options}) to identify all packages implicated in the error.
@item
Presents the candidate packages via @code{completing-read}, ordered from most likely root cause to least likely, so the user can select the right one.
@item
Starts an interactive Claude Code session in the selected package's source directory (elpaca source directory if available, otherwise the directory of the library file on @code{load-path}).
@item
Once the session is ready, sends it the backtrace file path and asks it to identify and fix the bug.
@end enumerate

@node Branch navigation
@section Branch navigation

@findex claude-code-extras-create-branch
@findex claude-code-extras-switch-branch
Claude Code's branching mechanism creates a new session forked from the current conversation. Over time, a single session can accumulate several branches (and branches of branches). This section covers creating new branches from Emacs and navigating the resulting tree.

@menu
* Creating a branch::
* Switching branches::
* Automatic branch detection in the modeline::
@end menu

@node Creating a branch
@subsection Creating a branch

The command @code{claude-code-extras-create-branch} creates a new branch of the current Claude session and switches to it. It starts a new Claude process with @samp{--resume SESSION_ID --fork-session}, which tells the CLI to resume the conversation but under a fresh session ID@. The result is a new session that shares the full history of its parent but diverges from this point forward.

The new buffer is automatically named @samp{fork-HHMMSS} (using the current time) to avoid prompting for an instance name. After branching, you can interact with the new session independently while the original remains open in its buffer. Use @code{claude-code-extras-switch-branch} to navigate between them (@ref{Switching branches}).

@node Switching branches
@subsection Switching branches

The command @code{claude-code-extras-switch-branch} navigates between branches of the current session.

When invoked from a Claude Code buffer, the command reads the current session's ID from the status file, scans the project's session JSONL files to reconstruct the branching structure, and displays a tree-formatted selection interface via @code{consult--read}. Each entry shows the session's first user prompt (truncated to 60 characters), a formatted timestamp, and a @samp{*} marker on the current session. Tree-drawing characters (@samp{├─}, @samp{└─}, @samp{│}) visualize the parent-child relationships:

@example
let's redesign the recordings validation  Mar 29 02:28
├─ do the quick check                     Mar 29 03:15 *
│  └─ fix the edge case                   Mar 29 04:00
└─ try alternative approach                Mar 29 03:20
@end example

On selection, the command checks whether the target session is already running in an Emacs buffer. If so, it switches to that buffer directly. If the session is not running, it starts a new Claude Code session with @samp{--resume SESSION_ID} to reopen it. The new buffer is automatically named @samp{branch-XXXXXXXX} (using the first eight characters of the session ID) to avoid prompting for an instance name.

The scan is optimized in two phases. First, only the first line of each JSONL file in the project directory is read to extract session IDs and @code{forkedFrom} fields (fast). The full branch tree is then identified, and only the handful of sessions in the tree are read more deeply to extract their display prompts. For branched sessions, the first @emph{new} user message after the fork point is used as the label, so branches are distinguishable from their parent even though they share conversation history.

If the current session has no branches (and is not itself a branch), the command signals a user error.

@node Automatic branch detection in the modeline
@subsection Automatic branch detection in the modeline

When you run @samp{/branch} inside a Claude Code session, the CLI creates a new session within the same terminal buffer. The status poller detects this by comparing session IDs across polls: the first session ID seen is recorded as the original, and any subsequent change triggers a display name refresh. The modeline then shows a branch suffix appended to the normal display name, formatted as @samp{dir:instance:SHORTID} (where @samp{SHORTID} is the first eight characters of the new session ID). This makes it immediately visible that you are working in a branch rather than the original session.

