@node Buffer lifecycle
@section Buffer lifecycle

@findex claude-code-extras-protect-buffer
@findex claude-code-extras-setup-kill-on-exit
@findex claude-code-extras-fix-rendering
The function @code{claude-code-extras-protect-buffer} is a @code{kill-buffer-query-functions} member that prompts for confirmation before killing Claude buffers with live processes. It respects the @code{claude-code-extras-protect-buffers} user option (@ref{Buffer protection}).

The function @code{claude-code-extras-setup-kill-on-exit} wraps the process sentinel so that the buffer is automatically killed when the Claude process exits. This keeps the buffer list clean after normal session termination via @samp{/exit}.

The function @code{claude-code-extras-fix-rendering} sends a @samp{SIGWINCH} signal to the Claude process after the delay specified by @code{claude-code-extras-sigwinch-delay} (@ref{Terminal rendering}). This forces the TUI to re-query terminal dimensions and redraw correctly.

@findex claude-code-extras--send-escape-in-current-buffer
The function @code{claude-code-extras--send-escape-in-current-buffer} is an @samp{:around} advice on @code{claude-code-send-escape} that fixes @code{C-g} behavior when multiple Claude sessions share the same project directory.  The upstream implementation uses @code{claude-code--with-buffer}, which re-resolves the target buffer via @code{claude-code--get-or-prompt-for-buffer}.  When multiple sessions exist for the same project, this triggers a selection prompt instead of sending the escape to the current buffer.  The advice short-circuits the lookup: if the current buffer is already a Claude buffer, it sends the escape sequence directly; otherwise it falls through to the original function.

@node Status polling
@section Status polling

@findex claude-code-extras-start-status-polling
@findex claude-code-extras-stop-status-polling
The function @code{claude-code-extras-start-status-polling} begins periodic reading of the JSON status file written by the bundled statusline shell script. The parsed data is stored in the buffer-local variable @code{claude-code-extras--status-data} as a plist. Calling it multiple times is safe: any existing timer is canceled before a new one is created.

The function @code{claude-code-extras-stop-status-polling} cancels the timer and deletes the status file. As a safety net, the polling callback also cancels itself if the associated buffer has been killed.

@node Status accessors
@section Status accessors

@findex claude-code-extras-status-model
@findex claude-code-extras-status-cost
@findex claude-code-extras-status-context-percent
@findex claude-code-extras-status-token-count
@findex claude-code-extras-status-lines-added
@findex claude-code-extras-status-lines-removed
@findex claude-code-extras-status-duration-ms
@findex claude-code-extras-status-cache-read-tokens
@findex claude-code-extras-status-cache-total-tokens
The status accessor functions extract specific values from the parsed status data. Each returns @code{nil} if the status data is unavailable or the relevant key is missing.

@itemize
@item
@code{claude-code-extras-status-model} returns the model display name (e.g. ``Claude Opus 4.6'').
@item
@code{claude-code-extras-status-cost} returns the total session cost in USD@.
@item
@code{claude-code-extras-status-context-percent} returns the context window usage as a percentage.
@item
@code{claude-code-extras-status-token-count} returns the total input token count.
@item
@code{claude-code-extras-status-lines-added} and @code{claude-code-extras-status-lines-removed} return line-change statistics.
@item
@code{claude-code-extras-status-duration-ms} returns the total session duration in milliseconds.
@item
@code{claude-code-extras-status-cache-read-tokens} returns the cache read input token count for the current turn.
@item
@code{claude-code-extras-status-cache-total-tokens} returns the sum of all input token categories (input, cache creation, and cache read) for the current turn.
@end itemize

These functions are designed to be called from modeline constructors (e.g. @samp{doom-modeline-extras.el}) to display live session statistics.

@node Usage accessors
@section Usage accessors

@findex claude-code-extras-status-session-usage
@findex claude-code-extras-status-weekly-usage
@findex claude-code-extras-status-session-reset
@findex claude-code-extras-status-weekly-reset
The usage accessor functions extract values from the data fetched by @code{claude-code-extras-start-usage-polling} (@ref{Usage polling}). Unlike the status accessors (@ref{Status accessors}), which read buffer-local data from a per-session status file, these functions look up the current buffer's account in the per-account usage hash table. Each returns @code{nil} if usage data has not yet been fetched for that account.

@itemize
@item
@code{claude-code-extras-status-session-usage} returns the 5-hour session utilization as a percentage.
@item
@code{claude-code-extras-status-weekly-usage} returns the 7-day weekly utilization as a percentage.
@item
@code{claude-code-extras-status-session-reset} returns the 5-hour session reset time as an ISO 8601 string.
@item
@code{claude-code-extras-status-weekly-reset} returns the 7-day weekly reset time as an ISO 8601 string.
@end itemize

These functions are designed to be called from modeline constructors or other display code that needs to show plan utilization alongside the per-session statistics provided by the status accessors.

@node Alerts
@section Alerts

@findex claude-code-extras-notify
@findex claude-code-extras-alert-indicator
@findex claude-code-extras--handle-notification
The function @code{claude-code-extras--handle-notification} is a @code{claude-code-event-hook} listener that handles @samp{Notification} events from the CLI@.  It parses the notification JSON to determine the type and dispatches alerts accordingly: @samp{idle_prompt} (Claude finished and is waiting), @samp{permission_prompt} (a tool needs approval), and @samp{elicitation_dialog} (Claude is showing an input dialog).  For @samp{idle_prompt}, it also sets @code{claude-code-extras--waiting-for-input} to the current time (via @code{current-time}), which is used by @code{claude-code-extras-jump-to-waiting} to identify the most recently waiting session.

The function @code{claude-code-extras-notify} combines the default modeline pulse with optional OS alerts.  When @code{claude-code-extras-alert-on-ready} is non-@code{nil}, it dispatches visual and/or audible alerts according to @code{claude-code-extras-alert-style} (@ref{Alert options}).  It is called by the notification handler rather than installed directly as @code{claude-code-notification-function} (which is set to the default modeline-only callback to avoid double-alerting from the terminal bell).

The Notification hook that delivers these events is auto-configured at package load time via @code{claude-code-extras-ensure-notification-hook-config} (@ref{Auto-setup}), so no manual @samp{settings.json} editing is required.

The function @code{claude-code-extras-alert-indicator} returns a bell icon string reflecting the current alert state. It is intended for use in modeline segments or header lines to give a visual indication of whether alerts are active.

@findex claude-code-extras--has-background-tasks-p
The function @code{claude-code-extras--has-background-tasks-p} returns non-@code{nil} when the current (or given) Claude session buffer has active background work.  It scans the tail of the terminal buffer for Claude Code's status-line indicator, which renders @samp{· N shells} or @samp{· N monitors} when background Bash processes or Task agents are still running.  It is registered as the backend's @code{:has-background-tasks-p} function, allowing the shared session switcher to highlight idle-but-busy sessions with a distinct face ( in the @samp{ai-extras} manual).

@node Modeline integration
@section Modeline integration

@findex claude-code-extras-set-modeline
The function @code{claude-code-extras-set-modeline} activates the @samp{claude-code} doom-modeline segment for the current buffer. It also starts status polling if it is not already active (@ref{Status polling}). This function is added to @code{claude-code-start-hook} automatically.

@node Snippet insertion
@section Snippet insertion

@findex claude-code-extras--consult-yasnippet
@findex claude-code-extras--expand-snippet-to-text
The function @code{claude-code-extras--consult-yasnippet} is an @samp{:around} advice on @code{consult-yasnippet} that makes snippet insertion work in Eat terminal buffers (such as Claude Code sessions).  The upstream @code{consult-yasnippet} captures buffer positions at invocation time and manipulates them on return (via @code{delete-region}, @code{insert}, and @code{goto-char}) for preview cleanup.  In an Eat buffer the terminal emulator modifies the buffer asynchronously, so those positions become stale and cause @samp{args-out-of-range} errors.

The advice detects @code{eat-mode} and replaces the entire flow: it calls @code{consult-yasnippet--candidates} and @code{consult--read} without a @samp{:state} function (no preview or buffer manipulation), then expands the selected template to plain text via @code{claude-code-extras--expand-snippet-to-text}, which creates a temporary buffer, enables @code{yas-minor-mode}, expands the snippet, commits all active snippet fields to their defaults, and returns the resulting string.  Newlines in the expanded text are converted to Alt+Enter sequences (@code{ESC CR}) so that Claude Code's TUI treats them as multi-line input.  The final text is sent through @code{eat-term-send-string}.

In non-Eat buffers the advice delegates to the original function unchanged.

@findex claude-code-extras--try-expand-snippet-at-prompt
@findex claude-code-extras-snippet-tab
@findex claude-code-extras-setup-snippet-keys
The function @code{claude-code-extras--try-expand-snippet-at-prompt} enables TAB-triggered snippet expansion at the terminal prompt.  It searches backward from @code{point-max} for the @samp{❯} prompt marker, extracts the user's input, and checks whether it ends with a yasnippet key.  When the input matches, the function sends DEL characters to erase the key from the terminal, then sends the expanded snippet text through @code{eat-term-send-string}.  When multiple keys match, the longest one wins.

The minor mode @code{claude-code-extras--snippet-keys-mode} overrides TAB in Claude Code buffers to call @code{claude-code-extras-snippet-tab}, which tries snippet expansion first and falls through to @code{eat-self-input} otherwise.  The function @code{claude-code-extras-setup-snippet-keys} activates this mode from @code{claude-code-start-hook} when Copilot integration is disabled.  When Copilot is enabled, the Copilot TAB handler (@code{claude-code-extras--copilot-tab}) chains through snippet expansion before falling through to eat, so a separate mode is not needed.

@node Copilot integration
@section Copilot integration

@findex claude-code-extras-setup-copilot
@findex claude-code-extras-teardown-copilot
The function @code{claude-code-extras-setup-copilot} enables Copilot in the current Claude Code buffer. It is added to @code{claude-code-start-hook} automatically and guards on @code{claude-code-extras-copilot-enabled} (@ref{Copilot options}), the presence of an Eat terminal, and the availability of the @samp{copilot} package. When all conditions are met, it bridges three mechanical mismatches between Copilot and Eat terminal buffers:

@enumerate
@item
@strong{Language ID@.} Installs @samp{:around} advice on @code{copilot--get-language-id} that returns @samp{"plaintext"} in Claude Code buffers.  The default language ID @samp{"eat"} is unknown to the Copilot server.

@item
@strong{Document URI@.} Sets @code{buffer-file-name} to a temporary file path so that @code{copilot--get-uri} returns a @samp{file://} URI@.  The Copilot server silently ignores the virtual @samp{buffer://} URIs that non-file buffers produce.

@item
@strong{Acceptance routing.} Installs @samp{:around} advice on @code{copilot-accept-completion} that sends accepted text through @code{eat-term-send-string} instead of using @code{delete-region~/~insert}, which would corrupt the terminal state.  Newlines in accepted completions are converted to Alt+Enter sequences so that Claude Code's TUI treats them as multi-line input rather than prompt submission.  The advice also sends the appropriate Copilot telemetry for both full and partial acceptance.
@end enumerate

Additionally, the setup installs a @code{post-command-hook} handler that schedules a debounced document sync and completion request after each user command.  Two issues make copilot's built-in triggers ineffective in Eat buffers: (a) Eat's process filter runs with @code{inhibit-modification-hooks} bound to t, so neither @code{after-change-functions} nor @code{track-changes} (which copilot uses for incremental document sync) detect buffer modifications; (b) the terminal echo from a keystroke arrives asynchronously after @code{post-command-hook} has already fired.  The handler works around both problems by waiting 0.3 seconds for the echo to land, then sending a full-document @code{textDocument/didChange} notification to the Copilot server before requesting completions.  The completion request is positioned at the TUI input prompt (identified by the @samp{❯} marker) rather than at the terminal cursor, which may be on a status-bar or border line due to TUI rendering updates.

Copilot's @code{track-changes} handler is unregistered after @code{copilot-mode} enables, since it cannot function in Eat buffers and would otherwise cause ``Recovering from confusing calls to before/after-change-functions'' errors.  Copilot's own @code{post-command-hook} handler (@code{copilot--post-command}) is also removed, since it would call @code{copilot-complete} without syncing the document first.

An @samp{:around} advice on @code{copilot--show-completion} relocates the overlay to the TUI prompt line after the original function creates it.  In eat buffers the line numbers in the server's range drift because the buffer changes between sync and response, so the overlay often ends up on a TUI chrome line.  The advice lets the original function create the overlay, then moves it to the prompt and re-renders the ghost text at the correct position, and finally moves point there so the Emacs cursor sits at the ghost text boundary.

Completions are truncated to a single line via @samp{:around} advice on @code{copilot--set-overlay-text}, preventing ghost text from extending past the TUI input area into the terminal chrome below.

A predicate is added to @code{copilot-disable-predicates} that suppresses completions while @code{buffer-read-only} is non-nil.

@enumerate
@item
@strong{TAB acceptance.}  Eat's semi-char-mode keymap binds TAB to @code{eat-self-input}, which takes priority over copilot's keymap overlay.  A buffer-local minor mode (@code{claude-code-extras--copilot-keys-mode}) overrides TAB so that it accepts the visible completion when one exists, and falls through to @code{eat-self-input} otherwise.
@end enumerate

The function @code{claude-code-extras-teardown-copilot} clears the buffer-local Copilot integration flag and cancels any pending change timer when the buffer is killed. It is added to @code{kill-buffer-hook} automatically.

@node Non-interactive execution internals
@section Non-interactive execution internals

@findex claude-code-extras--build-cli-args
@findex claude-code-extras--run-prompt
@findex claude-code-extras--batch-parse-stream-json
The function @code{claude-code-extras--build-cli-args} assembles the command-line arguments for @samp{claude -p}, incorporating allowed tools, max turns, system prompt, and model override. It accepts keyword arguments that default to the corresponding @samp{claude-code-extras-batch-*} customization variables.

The function @code{claude-code-extras--run-prompt} is the single-shot runner that spawns a @samp{claude -p} process asynchronously. It takes a prompt string and keyword arguments @samp{:dir}, @samp{:callback}, @samp{:allowed-tools}, @samp{:system-prompt}, @samp{:model}, and @samp{:max-turns}. Any @samp{CLAUDE_CODE} environment variables are stripped from @code{process-environment} to prevent nested-session errors. When the process finishes, the sentinel parses the stream-json output and calls the callback with a result plist containing @samp{:exit-code}, @samp{:duration}, @samp{:cost}, @samp{:text}, @samp{:session-id}, and @samp{:raw}. Both @code{claude-code-extras-run-skill} and @code{claude-code-extras--batch-run-next} delegate to this function.

The function @code{claude-code-extras--batch-parse-stream-json} parses the raw stream-json output from @samp{claude -p} into a plist with @samp{:text} (concatenated assistant messages), @samp{:cost}, and @samp{:session-id}.

@node Skill runner internals
@section Skill runner internals

@findex claude-code-extras--parse-skill-frontmatter
@findex claude-code-extras--discover-skills
@findex claude-code-extras--skill-display-result
The function @code{claude-code-extras--parse-skill-frontmatter} reads a @samp{SKILL.md} file and extracts the YAML frontmatter into a plist with keys @samp{:name}, @samp{:description}, @samp{:argument-hint}, and @samp{:user-invocable}.

The function @code{claude-code-extras--discover-skills} scans @samp{~/.claude/skills/} and the current project's @samp{.claude/skills/} for @samp{SKILL.md} files, parses their frontmatter, and returns a list of skill plists. Project skills shadow global skills with the same name. Skills with @samp{user-invocable: false} are excluded.

The function @code{claude-code-extras--skill-display-result} displays the skill result.  When the skill created its own buffer (e.g. via @samp{emacsclient}), the metadata (cost, duration, session) is added to that buffer and no separate buffer is created.  Otherwise a @samp{*Claude Skill: <name>*} buffer is created with the full output.

@node Batch TODO internals
@section Batch TODO internals

@findex claude-code-extras--batch-collect-todos
@findex claude-code-extras--batch-format-prompt
@findex claude-code-extras--batch-start
@findex claude-code-extras--batch-run-next
@findex claude-code-extras--batch-finish
The function @code{claude-code-extras--batch-collect-todos} uses @code{org-map-entries} to find entries with a TODO state in the given scope. For each entry, it extracts the heading text (without TODO keyword, priority, tags, or comment) and the body text (excluding property drawers and child subtrees).

The function @code{claude-code-extras--batch-format-prompt} combines an entry's title and body into a single prompt string. If the body is empty, the title alone is used.

The function @code{claude-code-extras--batch-start} initializes the processing state, creates a timestamped log subdirectory, and kicks off the async chain.

The function @code{claude-code-extras--batch-run-next} pops the next entry from the queue, formats the prompt, and delegates to @code{claude-code-extras--run-prompt}. The callback saves raw output to a log file, records the result, optionally commits changes, and recurses to process the next entry.

The function @code{claude-code-extras--batch-finish} constructs and displays the @samp{*Claude Batch Results*} summary buffer with aggregate statistics and per-entry details.

@node Auto-setup
@section Auto-setup

@findex claude-code-extras-ensure-statusline-config
@findex claude-code-extras-ensure-stop-hook-config
@findex claude-code-extras-ensure-notification-hook-config
The function @code{claude-code-extras-ensure-statusline-config} checks @samp{~/.claude/settings.json} for a @samp{statusLine} entry and adds one if absent, pointing to the bundled shell script. This ensures that the status JSON file is written for every Claude session without manual configuration.

The function @code{claude-code-extras-ensure-stop-hook-config} similarly checks for a @samp{Stop} hook entry and adds one if absent, pointing to the bundled hook wrapper script. This enables the stop-event detection that powers scroll-to-bottom and pending theme application.

The function @code{claude-code-extras-ensure-notification-hook-config} checks for a @samp{Notification} hook entry and adds one if absent or empty, pointing to the bundled notification forwarding script.  It handles both the case where the @samp{Notification} key exists with an empty array and where the key is missing entirely.  This enables the alert system (@ref{Alerts}) to receive @samp{Notification} events (idle prompts, permission requests, elicitation dialogs) from the CLI via @code{emacsclient}.

All three functions run automatically when the package is loaded.

@node Transient menu
@chapter Transient menu

@findex claude-code-extras-menu
The command @code{claude-code-extras-menu} opens a transient menu that provides quick access to all major features of the package.  The menu is organized into six groups:

@itemize
@item
@strong{Sessions.} Start or switch between sessions (@code{claude-code-extras-start-or-switch}, @ref{Session switching}), navigate branches (@code{claude-code-extras-switch-branch}, @ref{Branch navigation}), create a new branch (@code{claude-code-extras-create-branch}, @ref{Creating a branch}), restart the current session in place (@code{claude-code-extras-restart}), and perform a session handoff (@code{claude-code-extras-handoff}).
@item
@strong{Tools.} Run a skill (@code{claude-code-extras-run-skill}, @ref{Skill runner}), process batch TODOs (@code{claude-code-extras-batch-todos}, @ref{Batch TODO processing}), send the TODO at point to an interactive session (@code{claude-code-extras-send-todo-at-point}, @ref{Send TODO at point}), audit a project (@code{claude-code-extras-audit-project}, @ref{Project audit}), debug a backtrace (@code{claude-code-extras-debug-backtrace}, @ref{Debug backtrace}), and browse session logs (@code{agent-log-menu}).
@item
@strong{Alerts & status.} Toggle alerts (@code{claude-code-extras-toggle-alert}, @ref{Toggling alerts}), start or stop status polling (@ref{Status polling}), and start or stop usage polling (@code{claude-code-extras-start-usage-polling}, @code{claude-code-extras-stop-usage-polling}, @ref{Usage polling}).
@item
@strong{Buffer.} Kill-on-exit setup (@code{claude-code-extras-setup-kill-on-exit}), rendering fixes (@code{claude-code-extras-fix-rendering}), and scrollback truncation control (@code{claude-code-extras-disable-scrollback-truncation}).  See @ref{Buffer lifecycle}.
@item
@strong{Setup.} Ensure statusline, notification hook, and stop hook configurations are present in @samp{~/.claude/settings.json}.  See @ref{Auto-setup}.
@item
@strong{Options.} An account infix (@code{-a}) that displays and selects the active Claude account (@ref{Multi-account support}), plus toggleable infixes for five boolean user options: @code{claude-code-extras-alert-on-ready} (@ref{Alert options}), @code{claude-code-extras-protect-buffers} (@ref{Buffer protection}), @code{claude-code-extras-sync-theme} (@ref{Theme sync}), @code{claude-code-extras-copilot-enabled} (@ref{Copilot options}), and @code{claude-code-extras-warn-kill-with-branches} (@ref{Buffer protection}).  Each infix displays its current value and stays in the transient after toggling, so you can adjust multiple options in one invocation.
@end itemize

